					<h4>Western Book Roundup</h4>
		
		<h1>In Search of the Literature of the Urban West</h1>
		<h2><i></i></h2>
		<div class="text-feature_print">
							<p>By Jenny Shank, 12-26-07</p>
			
							<table width="25" align="right" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0">
					<tr>
						<td>&nbsp;</td>
						<td><img src="http://www.newwest.net/images/thumbnails_feature/conoveraspen_thumb.jpg" align="right" width="97" height="150" /></td>
					</tr>
					<tr><td><img src="http://www.newwest.net/images/spacer.gif" width="1" height="3" border="0" /></td></tr>

					
					<tr><td><img src="http://www.newwest.net/images/spacer.gif" width="1" height="3" border="0" /></td></tr>
				</table>
			
							<p>I recently received a question from a reader that stumped me.&nbsp; <a target="_blank" href="http://greatestshow.blogspot.com/" title="Michael Downs">Michael Downs</a>, <a target="_blank" href="http://www.umt.edu/journalism/news_pages/archives/April/April07/April1.07/michaeldowns.htm" title="a writer">a writer</a> and professor of Creative Writing at Towson University, wrote in to ask if I could suggest any literary nonfiction books set in a Western city (not a town) in which that city &#8220;seems to be or is a character&#8221; for a panel discussion he&#8217;s organizing on this topic.&nbsp; Downs says he&#8217;s found a number of such books set in the industrial northeast, and wants to balance the panel geographically.
</p>
<p>
My mind was totally blank, particularly about the cities he mentioned--Salt Lake, Denver, and Albuquerque.&nbsp; I&#8217;ve read a number of good histories of my hometown, Denver, such as those by Tom Noel and Phil Goodstein, but can&#8217;t think of a literary, narrative nonfiction book set in Denver.&nbsp; The best suggestion I could come up with was <a target="_blank" href="http://www.tedconover.com/" title="Ted Conover's">Ted Conover&#8217;s</a> book on Aspen, <i><a target="_blank" href="http://www.tedconover.com/whiteout.html" title="Whiteout: Lost in Aspen">Whiteout: Lost in Aspen</a></i>, but Aspen isn&#8217;t exactly a city.&nbsp; I&#8217;m hoping that some readers will have some suggestions.
</p>
<p>
While I was thinking about Downs&#8217; nonfiction question, I realized that the same dearth applies to fiction set in the cities of the mountain West.&nbsp; As I&#8217;ve discussed before, there are hardly any novels set in contemporary Denver--characters in <a target="_blank" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kent_Haruf" title="Kent Haruf's">Kent Haruf&#8217;s</a> last two novels have passed through the Mile High City, as did some characters in <a target="_blank" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/E._Annie_Proulx" title="Annie Proulx's">Annie Proulx&#8217;s</a> last novel, <I><a target="_blank" href="http://www.amazon.com/That-Old-Ace-Hole-Novel/dp/0743242483" title="That Old Ace in the Hole">That Old Ace in the Hole</a></I>.&nbsp; But these books are largely set elsewhere, and Denver is treated as the dirty, ominous big city, especially in Haruf&#8217;s books.&nbsp; Where&#8217;s the literary love for Denver?&nbsp; I&#8217;m looking forward to reading a novel coming out this spring that&#8217;s set in Denver by a grad school friend of mine, Tara Yellen&#8217;s <i><a target="_blank" href="http://search.barnesandnoble.com/booksearch/isbninquiry.asp?r=1&amp;ean=9781932961485" title="After Hours at the Almost Home">After Hours at the Almost Home</a></i> (<a target="_blank" href="http://www.unbridledbooks.com/" title="Unbridled Books">Unbridled Books</a>).
</p>
<p>
I&#8217;ve read some good Western urban literature set in Texas (such as <a target="_blank" href="http://www.austinchronicle.com/gyrobase/Issue/story?oid=oid%3A81167" title="Dagoberto Gilb's">Dagoberto Gilb&#8217;s</a> charming, quirky first novel, <i><a target="_blank" href="http://books.google.com/books?id=mej6lELKmM0C&amp;dq=dagoberto+gilb+last+known+residence+of&amp;pg=PP1&amp;ots=KtCMCAPnI7&amp;sig=OIJgYqCmW_EiFcnCCy0-poSrZ0U&amp;hl=en&amp;prev=http://www.google.com/search?q=dagoberto+gilb+last+known+residence+of&amp;ie=utf-8&amp;oe=utf-8&amp;rls=org.mozilla:en-US:official&amp;client=firefox-a&amp;sa=X&amp;oi=print&amp;ct=title&amp;cad=one-book-with-thumbnail#PPP1,M1" title="The Last Known Residence of Mickey Acu&#241;a">The Last Known Residence of Mickey Acu&#241;a</a></i>) and California (such as <a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/topic/article/an_interview_with_alex_espinoza/C39/L39/" title="Alex Espinoza">Alex Espinoza</a>&#8216;s <i><a target="_blank" href="http://www.randomhouse.com/catalog/display.pperl?isbn=9781400065394" title="Still Water Saints">Still Water Saints</a></i>), but here closer to the Rockies where the air is thinner, the bookshelves of urban lit thin out too.
</p>
<p>
As I pondered this question further, I thought about the covers of the books in my recent <a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/topic/article/best_in_the_west_favorite_books_of_2007/C39/L39/" title="Best of 2007">Best of 2007</a> <a target="_blank" href="http://www.newwest.net/topic/article/bes/C39/L39/" title="reading list">reading list</a>.&nbsp; And yes, I know you can&#8217;t judge a book by its cover, but I couldn&#8217;t help but notice that most of the covers feature an image of an animal, a rider, or a natural landscape.&nbsp; Do publishers refuse to publish anything set in the urban West, or are writers just not writing it?
</p>
<p>
I asked Michael Downs, and he wrote back: &#8220;I&#8217;ll bet you&#8217;re right about most publishers being more interested in the rural West. I wonder if most writers share that same interest. For years I&#8217;ve sensed a romanticism to contemporary literature about the West, but couldn&#8217;t quite put my finger on it. The books I read didn&#8217;t treat their subjects romantically. Most are hard-core realism. But now I wonder whether there&#8217;s a kind of romanticism in the choice of that subject, no matter how the subject is treated. And I wonder whether the accumulation of so many writers and publishers choosing the rural West for subject matter (or the great Western landscape, or fly fishing, or whatever) constitutes its own kind of romanticism regardless of how the subject is treated.&#8221;
</p>
<p>
So what do you think?&nbsp; Am I overlooking some notable literature of the urban West (particularly that of the cities of the Rocky Mountain West), or is it just not out there?&nbsp; And do you agree that publishers and/or writers treat the West in the romantic way that Downs has suggested?&nbsp; I for one am stumped.
</p>
<p>
Have some regional literary news or events to share?&nbsp; If so,  <script type="text/javascript">
